_source.text: After going out just under 1.95, 10yr yields are already down under 1.90 at the start of the European session after S&P downgraded Spain right after Domestic bond markets closed (so much for phantom forces of resistance...) If this move is maintained throughout the overnight session, and isn't "undone" by better-than-expected GDP, it will be seen as the first attempt at kick-starting momentum after the recent sideways slide between 1.95-ish and 2.04-ish 10yr yields.
